{
  "A constant force of 10 N pushes an object 5 m along the direction of the force. How much work is done?": "",
  "50 J": "",
  "2 J": "",
  "100 J": "",
  "15 J": "",
  "Work = F * d * cos(0°) = 10 N * 5 m * 1 = 50 J.": "",
  "A 3 kg object moves at 4 m/s. What is its kinetic energy?": "",
  "6 J": "",
  "24 J": "",
  "48 J": "",
  "12 J": "",
  "KE = ½mv² = ½(3)(4²) = ½(3)(16) = 24 J.": "",
  "A force of 20 N is applied at 60° to the displacement over a distance of 4 m. What is the work done?": "",
  "69.3 J": "",
  "20 J": "",
  "80 J": "",
  "40 J": "",
  "W = Fd cos θ = 20(4)cos 60° = 80(0.5) = 40 J.": "",
  "A spring with k = 200 N/m is compressed 0.3 m from equilibrium. What is the work done by the spring force when it returns to equilibrium?": "",
  "18 J": "",
  "30 J": "",
  "60 J": "",
  "9 J": "",
  "The work done by a spring returning to equilibrium is W = ½kx² = ½(200)(0.3²) = ½(200)(0.09) = 9 J.": "",
  "A 2 kg object initially at rest has 50 J of net work done on it. What is its final speed?": "",
  "5 m/s": "",
  "10 m/s": "",
  "25 m/s": "",
  "7.07 m/s": "",
  "By the Work-Energy Theorem, W_net = ΔKE = ½mv². So 50 = ½(2)v², giving v² = 50, and v ≈ 7.07 m/s.": "",
  "A force F(x) = 6x N acts on a particle from x = 0 to x = 3 m. What is the total work done?": "",
  "54 J": "",
  "27 J": "",
  "W = ∫₀³ 6x dx = 6(x²/2)|₀³ = 3(9) = 27 J.": "",
  "The net work done on a 5 kg object changes its speed from 2 m/s to 6 m/s. What is the net work?": "",
  "90 J": "",
  "W_net = ½mv_f² - ½mv_i² = ½(5)(36) - ½(5)(4) = 90 - 10 = 80 J.": "",
  "A force does -30 J of work on a moving object. What happens to its kinetic energy?": "",
  "It increases by 30 J": "",
  "It doubles": "",
  "It decreases by 30 J": "",
  "It stays the same": "",
  "By the Work-Energy Theorem, W_net = ΔKE. Negative work means the kinetic energy decreases by 30 J.": "",
  "A spring with k = 400 N/m is stretched from x = 0.1 m to x = 0.3 m. How much work is done by the applied force?": "",
  "16 J": "",
  "8 J": "",
  "Work done by the applied force on a spring = ½k(x₂² - x₁²) = ½(400)(0.09 - 0.01) = 200(0.08) = 16 J.": "",
  "If the kinetic energy of a particle doubles, by what factor does its speed increase?": "",
  "2": "",
  "√2": "",
  "4": "",
  "½": "",
  "KE = ½mv². If KE doubles, v² doubles, so v increases by a factor of √2.": "",
